        <p>
            When writing Index Notation we represent it as:
        </p>
        <p>
            <me>
                a^n
            </me>
        </p>
        <p>
            Where:
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>a</m> is the base (the number being multiplied).
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>n</m> is the <m>exponent/ index /power</m> (the number of times the base is multiplied by itself).
        </p>
        <p>
            Therefore given <m>x</m> as a whole number;
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>
                x^a = x \times x \times x</m> .......(<m>a </m> is the number of times <m>x</m> is repeated)
            
        </p>
        <p>
            <term>Example:</term>
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>a^2</m> = <m>a \times a</m>  (<m>a</m>  repeated twice)
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>2^3</m> = <m>2 \times 2 \times 2</m>  (<m>2</m>  repeated thrice)
        </p>
        <p>
            <m> = 8</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>5^4</m> = <m>5 \times 5 \times 5 \times 5</m>  (<m>5</m>  repeated four times)
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>= 625</m>
        </p>
    </subsubsection>


    <subsubsection xml:id="subsec-laws-of-indices">
        <title>Laws of Indices</title>

        <p>
            When we need to work with indices efficiently, we use a set of rules called the Laws of Indices. They are useful in carrying out operations involving indices.
        </p>
        <p>
            <term>a) Product Law</term>
        </p>
        <p>
            When multiplying numbers with the same base, add their powers.
        </p>
        <p>
            i.e <m> a^m \times a^n = a^{m + n}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <term>Example:</term>
        </p>
        <p>
            <me>3^2 \times 3^4 = 3^{2 + 4}</me> 
        </p>
        <p>
            <me>
                = 3^6
            </me>
        </p>

        <p>
            <term>b) Quotient Law</term>
        </p>
        <p>
            When dividing numbers with the same base, subtract their powers.
        </p>
        <p>
            i.e <m> \frac {a^m}{a^n}</m> = <m>a^{m-n}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <term>Example:</term>
        </p>
        <p>
            <me>5^7 \div 5^3 = \frac {5^7}{5^3} = \frac {5 \times 5 \times 5 \times 5 \times 5 \times 5 \times 5}{5 \times 5 \times 5}</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            <me>= 5^{(7 - 3)} </me>
        </p>
        <p>
            <me>
                = 5^4 
            </me>
        </p>

        <p>
            <term>c) Power of a Power Law</term>
        </p>
        <p>
            When raising a power to another power, multiply the powers.
        </p>
        <p>
            i.e <m>(a^m)^n</m> = <m>a^{(m \times n)}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <term>Example:</term>
        </p>
        <p>
            <me>{(3^2)}^3 = (3 \times 3) \times (3 \times 3) \times (3 \times 3) </me> 
        </p>
        <p>
            <me>
                =3^{(2 \times 3)}
            </me>
        </p>
        <p>
            <me>
                = 3^6
            </me>
        </p>

        <p>
            <term>d) Power of a Product Law</term>
        </p>
        <p>
            When raising a power to a product factor, multiply the power to all factors inside the bracket.
        </p>
        <p>
            i.e <m>(ab)^n</m> = <m>a^n \times b^n</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <term>Example:</term>
        </p>
        <p>
            <me>(2 \times 3)^3 = 2^3 \times 3^3 </me> 
        </p>
        <p>
            <me>
                = 8 \times 27
            </me>
        </p>
        <p>
            <me>
                = 216
            </me>
        </p>

        <p>
            <term>e) Fractional Powers</term>
        </p>
        <p>
            A fractional power represents a root.
        </p>
        <p>
            i.e <m>(a^{\frac {m}{n}})</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <me> (a^m)^{\frac {1}{n}} = \sqrt [n]{a^m}</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            <term>Example:</term>
        </p>
        <p>
            Solve:
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker = "i)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>8^{\frac {1}{3}}</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <me>= \sqrt [3]{8^1}</me>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <me>
                            =2
                        </me>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Similarly we can say,
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <me>
                            8 = 2 \times 2 \times 2 = 2^3
                        </me>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <me>8^{\frac {1}{3}} = {(2^3)}^{\frac {1}{3}}</me>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <me>
                            = 2^{(3 \times \frac {1}{3})}
                        </me>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <me>
                            = 2
                        </me>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>(\frac {4}{5})^3</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <me>(\frac {a}{b})^3 = \frac {a^3}{b^3} </me>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <me>(\frac {4}{5})^3 = \frac {4^3}{5^3}</me>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <me>
                            = \frac {64}{125}
                        </me>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <table>
        <title>Summary of the Laws of Indices</title>
            <tabular top="medium" bottom="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
                <row>
                    <cell> Law </cell>
                    <cell> <m>Expression</m> </cell>
                    <cell> <m>Example</m> </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell> Product Law </cell>
                    <cell> <m>a^m \times a^n = a^{(m + n)}</m> </cell>
                    <cell> <m>2^3 \times 2^4 = 2^{(3 + 4)} = 2^7 = 128</m> </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell> Quotient Law </cell>
                    <cell> <m>a^m \div a^n = a^{(m - n)}</m> </cell>
                    <cell> <m>5^7 \div 5^3 = 5^{(7 - 3)} = 5^4</m> </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell> Power of a Power Law </cell>
                    <cell> <m>(a^m)^n = a^{(m \times n)}</m> </cell>
                    <cell> <m>(3^2)^3 = 3^{(2 \times 3)} = 3^6</m> </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell> Power of a Product Law </cell>
                    <cell> <m>(a \times b)^n = a^n \times b^n</m> </cell>
                    <cell> <m>(2 \times 3)^3 = 2^3 \times 3^3 = 216</m> </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell> Fractional Powers </cell>
                    <cell> <m>a^{(\frac {m}{n})} = n\sqrt {(a^m)}</m> </cell>
                    <cell> <m>8^{(\frac {1}{3})} = \sqrt[3]{8} = 2</m> </cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>

        <p>
            <term>Important</term>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The laws apply only when the bases are the same
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>

